The paper deals with the coordination and control of multiple robots, which is a core topic in robotics (cs.RO). The use of hierarchical clustering for identifying and representing spatially cohesive and segregated robot groups is a novel approach that involves the use of machine learning techniques, which could also place the paper in the sub-category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also presents a hybrid controller that is quadratic in the number of robots and algebraic in the dimension of the ambient space, which suggests that it could be relevant to the sub-category of mathematical aspects of robotics (cs.MA). The use of geometric realizations for navigation could also place the paper in the sub-category of computer vision and pattern recognition (cs.CV). Finally, the paper deals with the coordination and control of multiple robots, which could also be relevant to the sub-category of systems and control (cs.SY).
